('chunk_72c79bea1d7afa1e05','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Common Errors and Parallax Error','**Definition.** *Errors* are differences between a measured and true value. Common length, mass and time errors include zero errors (instrument not reading zero at start), reaction-time delays with stopwatches, and *parallax error* — a reading error caused by viewing a scale from an angle rather than straight on.

**Real-world example.** Reading a thermometer or measuring cylinder from above or below the meniscus gives a wrong value; only eye-level reading is correct.

**Analogy.** A car''s fuel gauge appears to point differently to the driver and the passenger — same needle, different angle, different reading.

**Why it matters.** Recognising and removing errors is central to MYP Criterion C (evaluating and improving a method).

**Described diagram.** A measuring cylinder with three eye positions: eye above reads too high, eye below reads too low, eye level with the meniscus reads correctly.

**Misconception.** *"A stopwatch gives the exact time."* Wrong because human reaction time (~0.2 s) adds error at start and stop. Corrective: repeat and average, or use light gates to reduce reaction error.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *Define* parallax error. (recall)
2. *Identify* one source of error when timing a runner with a handheld stopwatch. (apply)
3. *Suggest and justify* two improvements to reduce errors when measuring the length of a table. (evaluate)','{"common":2,"errors":6,"and":10,"parallax":3,"error":7,"definition":1,"are":1,"differences":1,"between":1,"measured":1,"true":1,"value":2,"length":2,"mass":1,"time":4,"include":1,"zero":2,"instrument":1,"not":1,"reading":5,"start":2,"reaction":3,"delays":1,"with":4,"stopwatches":1,"caused":1,"viewing":1,"scale":1,"from":2,"angle":2,"rather":1,"than":1,"straight":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"thermometer":1,"measuring":3,"cylinder":2,"above":2,"below":2,"the":6,"meniscus":2,"gives":2,"wrong":2,"only":1,"eye":5,"level":2,"correct":1,"analogy":1,"car":1,"fuel":1,"gauge":1,"appears":1,"point":1,"differently":1,"driver":1,"passenger":1,"same":1,"needle":1,"different":2,"why":1,"matters":1,"recognising":1,"removing":1,"central":1,"myp":1,"criterion":1,"evaluating":1,"improving":1,"method":1,"described":1,"diagram":1,"three":1,"positions":1,"reads":3,"too":2,"high":1,"low":1,"correctly":1,"misconception":1,"stopwatch":2,"exact":1,"because":1,"human":1,"adds":1,"stop":1,"corrective":1,"repeat":1,"average":1,"use":1,"light":1,"gates":1,"reduce":2,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"define":1,"recall":1,"identify":1,"one":1,"source":1,"when":2,"timing":1,"runner":1,"handheld":1,"apply":1,"suggest":1,"justify":1,"two":1,"improvements":1,"table":1,"evaluate":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_a2046028b7ca0497a2','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Distance vs Displacement','**Definition.** *Distance* is the total path length travelled (a scalar — size only). *Displacement* is the straight-line distance from start to finish in a given direction (a vector — size and direction).

**Real-world example.** Walk 3 m east then 3 m west: distance = 6 m, displacement = 0 m (back at start).

**Analogy.** Distance is how far your car''s odometer clocked up; displacement is how far you actually ended up from home "as the crow flies."

**Why it matters.** Confusing the two gives wrong velocities and misreads position-time graphs.

**Misconception.** *"Distance and displacement are always equal."* True only for straight-line, one-direction motion. Corrective: they differ whenever the path bends or reverses.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *Define* displacement. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the distance and displacement of a person who walks 4 m north then 3 m north. (apply)
3. *Explain* how a runner completing one lap of a track can have zero displacement but large distance. (analyse)','{"distance":8,"displacement":8,"definition":1,"the":6,"total":1,"path":2,"length":1,"travelled":1,"scalar":1,"size":2,"only":2,"straight":2,"line":2,"from":2,"start":2,"finish":1,"given":1,"direction":3,"vector":1,"and":4,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"walk":1,"east":1,"then":2,"west":1,"back":1,"analogy":1,"how":3,"far":2,"your":1,"car":1,"odometer":1,"clocked":1,"you":1,"actually":1,"ended":1,"home":1,"crow":1,"flies":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"confusing":1,"two":1,"gives":1,"wrong":1,"velocities":1,"misreads":1,"position":1,"time":1,"graphs":1,"misconception":1,"are":1,"always":1,"equal":1,"true":1,"for":1,"one":2,"motion":1,"corrective":1,"they":1,"differ":1,"whenever":1,"bends":1,"reverses":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"define":1,"recall":1,"calculate":1,"person":1,"who":1,"walks":1,"north":2,"apply":1,"explain":1,"runner":1,"completing":1,"lap":1,"track":1,"can":1,"have":1,"zero":1,"but":1,"large":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_47a9c98ac94352344b','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Speed vs Velocity (Velocity Definition)','**Definition.** *Speed* is the rate of change of distance (scalar). *Velocity* is the rate of change of displacement — speed in a stated direction (vector). Formula: velocity = displacement ÷ time.

> **Course note:** In Grade 7 the *direction* of velocity is used to distinguish it from speed conceptually, but numerical answers here do **not** require stating direction — treat magnitudes only.

**Real-world example.** A car''s speedometer shows speed; a GPS that says "moving north at 20 m/s" gives velocity.

**Analogy.** Speed is "how fast"; velocity is "how fast *and which way*."

**Why it matters.** Velocity, not speed, connects to displacement-time graphs and to acceleration.

**Worked example.** A cyclist covers 100 m in 20 s. Average speed = distance ÷ time = 100 ÷ 20 = **5 m/s**.

**Misconception.** *"Speed and velocity are the same word for the same thing."* Wrong because velocity carries direction and can be zero even at high speed (round trip). Corrective: speed is magnitude only; velocity includes direction.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *Define* velocity. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the average speed of a train travelling 240 m in 30 s. (apply)
3. *Distinguish* between speed and velocity using an example of circular motion. (analyse)','{"100":2,"240":1,"speed":13,"velocity":13,"definition":2,"the":6,"rate":2,"change":2,"distance":2,"scalar":1,"displacement":3,"stated":1,"direction":5,"vector":1,"formula":1,"time":3,"course":1,"note":1,"grade":1,"used":1,"distinguish":2,"from":1,"conceptually":1,"but":1,"numerical":1,"answers":1,"here":1,"not":2,"require":1,"stating":1,"treat":1,"magnitudes":1,"only":2,"real":1,"world":1,"example":3,"car":1,"speedometer":1,"shows":1,"gps":1,"that":1,"says":1,"moving":1,"north":1,"gives":1,"analogy":1,"how":2,"fast":2,"and":5,"which":1,"way":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"connects":1,"graphs":1,"acceleration":1,"worked":1,"cyclist":1,"covers":1,"average":2,"misconception":1,"are":1,"same":2,"word":1,"for":1,"thing":1,"wrong":1,"because":1,"carries":1,"can":1,"zero":1,"even":1,"high":1,"round":1,"trip":1,"corrective":1,"magnitude":1,"includes":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"define":1,"recall":1,"calculate":1,"train":1,"travelling":1,"apply":1,"between":1,"using":1,"circular":1,"motion":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_699785d10f2b49c62d','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Acceleration','**Definition.** Acceleration is the rate of change of velocity with time — how quickly speed increases or decreases. Formula: **a = (v − u) ÷ t**, unit m/s². (u = initial velocity, v = final velocity.)

**Real-world example.** A car speeding up from 0 to 20 m/s in 5 s accelerates at 4 m/s²; braking is negative acceleration (deceleration).

**Analogy.** Acceleration is how hard the "push in the back" feels when a car pulls away — the faster the velocity changes, the stronger the push.

**Why it matters.** Acceleration links force to motion (later: F = ma) and shapes velocity-time graphs.

**Worked example.** A car goes from 10 m/s to 30 m/s in 4 s.
a = (v − u) ÷ t = (30 − 10) ÷ 4 = 20 ÷ 4 = **5 m/s²**.

**Misconception.** *"An object moving fast must be accelerating."* Wrong because constant high speed means zero acceleration; acceleration is about *changing* velocity. Corrective: no change in velocity → no acceleration, however fast.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* the unit of acceleration. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the acceleration of a bike that slows from 12 m/s to 0 in 3 s. (apply)
3. *Explain* how an object can have a high speed but zero acceleration. (analyse)','{"acceleration":11,"definition":1,"the":9,"rate":1,"change":2,"velocity":7,"with":1,"time":2,"how":3,"quickly":1,"speed":3,"increases":1,"decreases":1,"formula":1,"unit":2,"initial":1,"final":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":2,"car":3,"speeding":1,"from":3,"accelerates":1,"braking":1,"negative":1,"deceleration":1,"analogy":1,"hard":1,"push":2,"back":1,"feels":1,"when":1,"pulls":1,"away":1,"faster":1,"changes":1,"stronger":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"links":1,"force":1,"motion":1,"later":1,"and":1,"shapes":1,"graphs":1,"worked":1,"goes":1,"misconception":1,"object":2,"moving":1,"fast":2,"must":1,"accelerating":1,"wrong":1,"because":1,"constant":1,"high":2,"means":1,"zero":2,"about":1,"changing":1,"corrective":1,"however":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"recall":1,"calculate":1,"bike":1,"that":1,"slows":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"can":1,"have":1,"but":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_6d64bf2817e25d199a','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Distance–Time / Position–Time / Displacement–Time Graphs','**Definition.** A distance-time (or position/displacement-time) graph plots how far an object is from a start point against time. The **slope (gradient) = speed/velocity**.

**Real-world example.** A GPS trace of a school bus stopping and starting — flat sections are stops, steep sections are fast stretches.

**Analogy.** Reading the graph is like reading a story: rising line = moving away, flat line = resting, steeper = faster.

**Why it matters.** Graphs turn a table of numbers into an instantly readable picture of motion and give speed from the slope.

**Described diagram.** Time on the x-axis, distance on the y-axis. A straight sloped line = constant speed; a horizontal line = at rest; a steeper line = higher speed; a curve that gets steeper = speeding up.

**Worked example (slope).** A line rises from 0 m to 40 m between t = 0 s and t = 8 s.
Slope = rise ÷ run = 40 ÷ 8 = **5 m/s**.

**Misconception.** *"A horizontal line on a distance-time graph means the object moves at constant speed."* Wrong — a flat line means distance isn''t changing, so the object is *stationary*. Corrective: constant speed is a *straight sloped* line; flat = at rest.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* what the slope of a distance-time graph represents. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the speed from a line rising 60 m over 12 s. (apply)
3. *Interpret* a distance-time graph that is steep, then flat, then steep again. (analyse)','{"distance":7,"time":10,"position":2,"displacement":2,"graphs":2,"definition":1,"graph":5,"plots":1,"how":1,"far":1,"object":3,"from":4,"start":1,"point":1,"against":1,"the":9,"slope":5,"gradient":1,"speed":7,"velocity":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":2,"gps":1,"trace":1,"school":1,"bus":1,"stopping":1,"and":3,"starting":1,"flat":5,"sections":2,"are":2,"stops":1,"steep":3,"fast":1,"stretches":1,"analogy":1,"reading":2,"like":1,"story":1,"rising":2,"line":10,"moving":1,"away":1,"resting":1,"steeper":3,"faster":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"turn":1,"table":1,"numbers":1,"into":1,"instantly":1,"readable":1,"picture":1,"motion":1,"give":1,"described":1,"diagram":1,"axis":2,"straight":2,"sloped":2,"constant":3,"horizontal":2,"rest":2,"higher":1,"curve":1,"that":2,"gets":1,"speeding":1,"worked":1,"rises":1,"between":1,"rise":1,"run":1,"misconception":1,"means":2,"moves":1,"wrong":1,"isn":1,"changing":1,"stationary":1,"corrective":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"what":1,"represents":1,"recall":1,"calculate":1,"over":1,"apply":1,"interpret":1,"then":2,"again":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_3a5809e2de8014a891','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Instantaneous vs Average Velocity','**Definition.** *Average velocity* = total displacement ÷ total time (over a whole journey). *Instantaneous velocity* is the velocity at a single instant — the reading a speedometer would show at that moment. (Definition only at this level.)

**Real-world example.** A 60 km trip in 1 hour gives an average of 60 km/h even though the speedometer showed 0, 80, and 40 km/h at different instants.

**Analogy.** Average velocity is your overall school-report grade; instantaneous velocity is your score on one particular question.

**Why it matters.** Explains why "average" hides the ups and downs of a real journey.

**Misconception.** *"Average velocity is the average of the highest and lowest speeds."* Wrong because it is total displacement over total time, which weights how long you spend at each speed. Corrective: use displacement ÷ time, not a simple mean of speeds.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *Define* instantaneous velocity. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the average velocity of a car covering 150 m in 30 s. (apply)
3. *Distinguish* between average and instantaneous velocity using a journey with traffic. (analyse)','{"150":1,"instantaneous":5,"average":9,"velocity":10,"definition":2,"total":4,"displacement":3,"time":3,"over":2,"whole":1,"journey":3,"the":7,"single":1,"instant":1,"reading":1,"speedometer":2,"would":1,"show":1,"that":1,"moment":1,"only":1,"this":1,"level":1,"real":2,"world":1,"example":1,"trip":1,"hour":1,"gives":1,"even":1,"though":1,"showed":1,"and":4,"different":1,"instants":1,"analogy":1,"your":2,"overall":1,"school":1,"report":1,"grade":1,"score":1,"one":1,"particular":1,"question":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"explains":1,"hides":1,"ups":1,"downs":1,"misconception":1,"highest":1,"lowest":1,"speeds":2,"wrong":1,"because":1,"which":1,"weights":1,"how":1,"long":1,"you":1,"spend":1,"each":1,"speed":1,"corrective":1,"use":1,"not":1,"simple":1,"mean":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"define":1,"recall":1,"calculate":1,"car":1,"covering":1,"apply":1,"distinguish":1,"between":1,"using":1,"with":1,"traffic":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_41f277d3d6f8eac769','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Velocity–Time Graphs','**Definition.** A velocity-time graph plots velocity against time. The **slope = acceleration**, and the **area under the line = distance travelled**.

**Real-world example.** A train pulling out: velocity rises (accelerating), holds steady (cruising), then falls (braking).

**Analogy.** The area under the graph is like counting the tiles beneath the line — each tile is a small chunk of distance, and they add up to the total.

**Why it matters.** One graph gives both acceleration (slope) and distance (area) — two answers from one picture.

**Described diagram.** Time on x-axis, velocity on y-axis. A rising straight line = constant acceleration; a horizontal line = constant velocity; a falling line = deceleration. To find distance while cruising at 10 m/s for 6 s, the area is a rectangle: 10 × 6 = 60 m. For a triangle (acceleration from rest), area = ½ × base × height.

**Worked example (area = distance).** An object accelerates from 0 to 12 m/s over 4 s (triangle), then holds 12 m/s for 3 s (rectangle).
Triangle area = ½ × 4 × 12 = 24 m. Rectangle area = 12 × 3 = 36 m. **Total distance = 60 m.**

**Misconception.** *"A horizontal line on a velocity-time graph means the object is stationary."* Wrong — a flat non-zero line means *constant velocity*; the object keeps moving. Only a line on the time axis (v = 0) means at rest. Corrective: on a v-t graph, flat = steady speed, not stopped.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* what the area under a velocity-time graph represents. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the distance travelled by an object moving at a constant 8 m/s for 5 s from its v-t graph. (apply)
3. *Analyse* a v-t graph with a rising line, a flat line, and a falling line, describing the motion in each stage. (analyse)','{"velocity":9,"time":7,"graphs":1,"definition":1,"graph":8,"plots":1,"against":1,"the":15,"slope":2,"acceleration":4,"and":4,"area":9,"under":3,"line":11,"distance":7,"travelled":2,"real":1,"world":1,"example":2,"train":1,"pulling":1,"out":1,"rises":1,"accelerating":1,"holds":2,"steady":2,"cruising":2,"then":2,"falls":1,"braking":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"counting":1,"tiles":1,"beneath":1,"each":2,"tile":1,"small":1,"chunk":1,"they":1,"add":1,"total":2,"why":1,"matters":1,"one":2,"gives":1,"both":1,"two":1,"answers":1,"from":4,"picture":1,"described":1,"diagram":1,"axis":3,"rising":2,"straight":1,"constant":4,"horizontal":2,"falling":2,"deceleration":1,"find":1,"while":1,"for":4,"rectangle":3,"triangle":3,"rest":2,"base":1,"height":1,"worked":1,"object":4,"accelerates":1,"over":1,"misconception":1,"means":3,"stationary":1,"wrong":1,"flat":3,"non":1,"zero":1,"keeps":1,"moving":2,"only":1,"corrective":1,"speed":1,"not":1,"stopped":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"what":1,"represents":1,"recall":1,"calculate":1,"its":1,"apply":1,"analyse":2,"with":1,"describing":1,"motion":1,"stage":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_ffebdef431265b14ae','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Formulae and Numerical Problems','**Key relationships used in this unit:**
- Average speed = total distance ÷ total time
- Average velocity = total displacement ÷ total time
- Acceleration: a = (v − u) ÷ t
- Slope of distance-time graph = speed
- Slope of velocity-time graph = acceleration; area under v-t graph = distance
- **v = u + at**
- **s = ut + ½at²**

**Worked example (v = u + at).** A car starts at u = 5 m/s and accelerates at a = 2 m/s² for t = 4 s.
v = u + at = 5 + (2 × 4) = 5 + 8 = **13 m/s**.

**Worked example (s = ut + ½at²).** Same car: distance in those 4 s.
s = ut + ½at² = (5 × 4) + ½ × 2 × 4² = 20 + ½ × 2 × 16 = 20 + 16 = **36 m**.

**Misconception.** *"You can use v = u + at even when the acceleration keeps changing."* Wrong because these equations assume *constant* acceleration. Corrective: only apply them to uniform acceleration; otherwise use graphs.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* the equation linking final velocity, initial velocity, acceleration and time. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the final velocity of an object starting from rest and accelerating at 3 m/s² for 6 s. (apply)
3. *Solve* for the distance travelled and *comment* on whether the constant-acceleration assumption is reasonable for a real car. (evaluate)

