('chunk_9c2dc9374fb0a8aaae','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Effects of Forces','**Definition.** Forces can change an object''s shape, size, speed, or direction of motion.

**Real-world example.** Squeezing clay changes its shape; a tennis racket changes a ball''s direction.

**Analogy.** A force is like an editor''s pen — it can reshape, resize, or redirect.

**Why it matters.** Every deformation and change of motion in engineering traces back to a force''s effect.

**Misconception.** *"Forces only make things move."* Wrong — forces also stretch, compress and bend objects that stay still (a stretched rubber band). Corrective: forces can change shape/size without any movement of the whole object.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* three effects a force can have. (recall)
2. *Identify* the effect of a force on a stretched spring. (apply)
3. *Explain* how a single kick can change both the speed and direction of a football. (analyse)','{"effects":2,"forces":5,"definition":1,"can":5,"change":4,"object":2,"shape":3,"size":2,"speed":2,"direction":3,"motion":2,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"squeezing":1,"clay":1,"changes":2,"its":1,"tennis":1,"racket":1,"ball":1,"analogy":1,"force":4,"like":1,"editor":1,"pen":1,"reshape":1,"resize":1,"redirect":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"every":1,"deformation":1,"and":3,"engineering":1,"traces":1,"back":1,"effect":2,"misconception":1,"only":1,"make":1,"things":1,"move":1,"wrong":1,"also":1,"stretch":1,"compress":1,"bend":1,"objects":1,"that":1,"stay":1,"still":1,"stretched":2,"rubber":1,"band":1,"corrective":1,"without":1,"any":1,"movement":1,"the":3,"whole":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"three":1,"have":1,"recall":1,"identify":1,"spring":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"how":1,"single":1,"kick":1,"both":1,"football":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_88932e0e73070b0380','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Balanced vs Unbalanced Forces & Free Body Diagrams','**Definition.** Forces are *balanced* when they cancel out (net force zero) — the object stays at rest or moves at constant velocity. Forces are *unbalanced* when one direction wins — the object accelerates. A *free body diagram* shows a single object with labelled arrows for each force; arrow length shows size, arrow direction shows the force''s direction. (Linear/one-line-of-action only at this level.)

**Real-world example.** A book resting on a table: weight down is balanced by the normal (reaction) force up. A floating boat: weight down balanced by upthrust up. A lamp hanging from a thread: weight down balanced by tension up.

**Analogy.** Balanced forces are a tug-of-war where both teams pull equally — the rope doesn''t move.

**Why it matters.** Recognising balance explains why resting, floating and hanging objects don''t accelerate, and free body diagrams are the standard tool for analysing forces.

**Described diagram.** For a resting book, draw a box with one arrow pointing down labelled "weight" and an equal-length arrow pointing up labelled "normal force." Equal arrows = balanced = no acceleration.

**Which force balances weight:**
- Resting on a surface → **normal (reaction) force** balances weight.
- Floating in a fluid → **upthrust** balances weight.
- Suspended by a thread → **tension** balances weight.

**Misconception.** *"If forces are balanced, the object must be still."* Wrong — balanced forces also allow *constant velocity* motion. Corrective: balanced = zero net force = no *change* in motion (rest OR steady speed).

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* what happens to an object when forces are balanced. (recall)
2. *Draw* a free body diagram for a box floating on water. (apply)
3. *Explain* which force balances the weight of a hanging lamp and why the lamp does not accelerate. (analyse)','{"balanced":11,"unbalanced":2,"forces":8,"free":4,"body":4,"diagrams":2,"definition":1,"are":6,"when":3,"they":1,"cancel":1,"out":1,"net":2,"force":9,"zero":2,"the":9,"object":5,"stays":1,"rest":2,"moves":1,"constant":2,"velocity":2,"one":3,"direction":3,"wins":1,"accelerates":1,"diagram":3,"shows":3,"single":1,"with":2,"labelled":3,"arrows":2,"for":4,"each":1,"arrow":4,"length":2,"size":1,"linear":1,"line":1,"action":1,"only":1,"this":1,"level":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"book":2,"resting":4,"table":1,"weight":9,"down":4,"normal":3,"reaction":2,"floating":4,"boat":1,"upthrust":2,"lamp":3,"hanging":3,"from":1,"thread":2,"tension":2,"analogy":1,"tug":1,"war":1,"where":1,"both":1,"teams":1,"pull":1,"equally":1,"rope":1,"doesn":1,"move":1,"why":3,"matters":1,"recognising":1,"balance":1,"explains":1,"and":4,"objects":1,"don":1,"accelerate":2,"standard":1,"tool":1,"analysing":1,"described":1,"draw":2,"box":2,"pointing":2,"equal":2,"acceleration":1,"which":2,"balances":5,"surface":1,"fluid":1,"suspended":1,"misconception":1,"must":1,"still":1,"wrong":1,"also":1,"allow":1,"motion":2,"corrective":1,"change":1,"steady":1,"speed":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"what":1,"happens":1,"recall":1,"water":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"does":1,"not":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_78620df5656dc11d44','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Mass vs Weight','**Definition.** *Mass* is the amount of matter in an object (kilograms), the same everywhere. *Weight* is the gravitational force on that mass (newtons): **weight = mass × gravitational field strength (W = mg)**, where g ≈ 10 N/kg on Earth.

**Real-world example.** An astronaut with mass 60 kg weighs about 600 N on Earth but only about 100 N on the Moon — same mass, less weight.

**Analogy.** Mass is how much "stuff" you''re made of; weight is how hard that stuff is being pulled down.

**Why it matters.** Confusing mass and weight leads to errors in force calculations and misunderstanding space travel.

**Worked example.** A 5 kg bag on Earth: W = mg = 5 × 10 = **50 N**.

**Misconception.** *"Mass and weight are the same thing."* Believed because scales in shops show "kg." Wrong because mass (kg) is constant while weight (N) changes with gravity. Corrective: mass is matter in kg; weight is a force in N that depends on g.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* the units of mass and weight. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the weight of a 12 kg object on Earth (g = 10 N/kg). (apply)
3. *Explain* why an object''s weight is less on the Moon but its mass is unchanged. (analyse)','{"100":1,"600":1,"mass":13,"weight":12,"definition":1,"the":8,"amount":1,"matter":2,"object":3,"kilograms":1,"same":3,"everywhere":1,"gravitational":2,"force":3,"that":3,"newtons":1,"field":1,"strength":1,"where":1,"earth":4,"real":1,"world":1,"example":2,"astronaut":1,"with":2,"weighs":1,"about":2,"but":2,"only":1,"moon":2,"less":2,"analogy":1,"how":2,"much":1,"stuff":2,"you":1,"made":1,"hard":1,"being":1,"pulled":1,"down":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"confusing":1,"and":4,"leads":1,"errors":1,"calculations":1,"misunderstanding":1,"space":1,"travel":1,"worked":1,"bag":1,"misconception":1,"are":1,"thing":1,"believed":1,"because":2,"scales":1,"shops":1,"show":1,"wrong":1,"constant":1,"while":1,"changes":1,"gravity":1,"corrective":1,"depends":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"units":1,"recall":1,"calculate":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"its":1,"unchanged":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_2bb7cb831c8f1e4cc2','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Pressure in Fluids','**Definition.** Pressure is force spread over an area: **pressure = force ÷ area** (P = F / A), unit pascal (Pa = N/m²). In fluids, pressure increases with depth and acts in all directions.

**Real-world example.** A dam is built thicker at the bottom because water pressure is greater at depth; sharp knives cut easily because a small area gives high pressure.

**Analogy.** Standing on snow in boots (small area, sink in) versus snowshoes (large area, stay on top) — same weight, different pressure.

**Why it matters.** Pressure explains diving, hydraulics, and why area matters for the same force.

**Worked example.** A force of 200 N acts on an area of 4 m².
P = F ÷ A = 200 ÷ 4 = **50 Pa**.

**Misconception.** *"A heavier object always exerts more pressure."* Wrong because pressure also depends on area — spreading the same force over more area lowers pressure. Corrective: pressure = force ÷ area, so area matters as much as force.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* the formula and unit for pressure. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the pressure when 500 N acts on 2 m². (apply)
3. *Explain* why water pressure on a dam increases with depth. (analyse)','{"200":2,"500":1,"pressure":15,"fluids":2,"definition":1,"force":7,"spread":1,"over":2,"area":11,"unit":2,"pascal":1,"increases":2,"with":2,"depth":3,"and":3,"acts":3,"all":1,"directions":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":2,"dam":2,"built":1,"thicker":1,"the":5,"bottom":1,"because":3,"water":2,"greater":1,"sharp":1,"knives":1,"cut":1,"easily":1,"small":2,"gives":1,"high":1,"analogy":1,"standing":1,"snow":1,"boots":1,"sink":1,"versus":1,"snowshoes":1,"large":1,"stay":1,"top":1,"same":3,"weight":1,"different":1,"why":3,"matters":3,"explains":1,"diving":1,"hydraulics":1,"for":2,"worked":1,"misconception":1,"heavier":1,"object":1,"always":1,"exerts":1,"more":2,"wrong":1,"also":1,"depends":1,"spreading":1,"lowers":1,"corrective":1,"much":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"formula":1,"recall":1,"calculate":1,"when":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_d9350ef5fc1cfd742d','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Hydraulic Press & Pascal''s Law','**Definition.** *Pascal''s Law:* pressure applied to an enclosed fluid is transmitted equally in all directions. A *hydraulic press* uses this: a small force on a small piston creates pressure that acts on a large piston, producing a large force.

**Real-world example.** Car brakes and hydraulic car jacks lift heavy loads with a light push.

**Analogy.** Squeezing one end of a water-filled balloon pushes out everywhere — the pressure travels through the whole fluid.

**Why it matters.** Hydraulics multiply force, letting small inputs move heavy machinery.

**Described diagram.** Two connected cylinders share a fluid. A small piston (small area) is pushed down; the same pressure acts on the large piston (large area), so its force is much bigger (F = P × A). The larger the area, the larger the output force.

**Misconception.** *"A hydraulic press creates extra energy from nothing."* Wrong — you gain force but the large piston moves a smaller distance, so work in ≈ work out (energy conserved). Corrective: force is multiplied, not energy.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* Pascal''s Law. (recall)
2. *Describe* how a hydraulic press multiplies force. (apply)
3. *Explain* why a hydraulic press does not break the law of conservation of energy. (evaluate)','{"hydraulic":6,"press":5,"pascal":3,"law":4,"definition":1,"pressure":4,"applied":1,"enclosed":1,"fluid":3,"transmitted":1,"equally":1,"all":1,"directions":1,"uses":1,"this":1,"small":5,"force":8,"piston":5,"creates":2,"that":1,"acts":2,"large":5,"producing":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"car":2,"brakes":1,"and":1,"jacks":1,"lift":1,"heavy":2,"loads":1,"with":1,"light":1,"push":1,"analogy":1,"squeezing":1,"one":1,"end":1,"water":1,"filled":1,"balloon":1,"pushes":1,"out":2,"everywhere":1,"the":10,"travels":1,"through":1,"whole":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"hydraulics":1,"multiply":1,"letting":1,"inputs":1,"move":1,"machinery":1,"described":1,"diagram":1,"two":1,"connected":1,"cylinders":1,"share":1,"area":3,"pushed":1,"down":1,"same":1,"its":1,"much":1,"bigger":1,"larger":2,"output":1,"misconception":1,"extra":1,"energy":4,"from":1,"nothing":1,"wrong":1,"you":1,"gain":1,"but":1,"moves":1,"smaller":1,"distance":1,"work":2,"conserved":1,"corrective":1,"multiplied":1,"not":2,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"recall":1,"describe":1,"how":1,"multiplies":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"does":1,"break":1,"conservation":1,"evaluate":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_c0d3dde3f06f7215ca','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Law of Conservation of Energy (in machines)','**Definition.** Energy cannot be created or destroyed, only transformed from one form to another; the total energy in a closed system stays constant.

**Real-world example.** In a simple machine, the energy you put in equals the useful energy out plus energy "lost" to friction as heat.

**Analogy.** Like money moved between bank accounts — the total never changes even as it shifts around.

**Why it matters.** It sets the limit on what any machine can do — you never get more energy out than you put in.

**Misconception.** *"A machine can produce more energy than it uses."* Wrong — a perpetual motion machine is impossible; some energy always becomes waste heat. Corrective: output energy ≤ input energy, always.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* the law of conservation of energy. (recall)
2. *Apply* the law to explain why a machine warms up during use. (apply)
3. *Evaluate* the claim that a machine is "100% efficient." (evaluate)','{"100":1,"law":3,"conservation":2,"energy":12,"machines":1,"definition":1,"cannot":1,"created":1,"destroyed":1,"only":1,"transformed":1,"from":1,"one":1,"form":1,"another":1,"the":8,"total":2,"closed":1,"system":1,"stays":1,"constant":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"simple":1,"machine":6,"you":3,"put":2,"equals":1,"useful":1,"out":2,"plus":1,"lost":1,"friction":1,"heat":2,"analogy":1,"like":1,"money":1,"moved":1,"between":1,"bank":1,"accounts":1,"never":2,"changes":1,"even":1,"shifts":1,"around":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"sets":1,"limit":1,"what":1,"any":1,"can":2,"get":1,"more":2,"than":2,"misconception":1,"produce":1,"uses":1,"wrong":1,"perpetual":1,"motion":1,"impossible":1,"some":1,"always":2,"becomes":1,"waste":1,"corrective":1,"output":1,"input":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"recall":1,"apply":2,"explain":1,"warms":1,"during":1,"use":1,"evaluate":2,"claim":1,"that":1,"efficient":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_62cd18ca62e3a65a2c','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Mechanical Advantage & Efficiency of Simple Machines','**Definition.** *Mechanical advantage (MA)* is how many times a machine multiplies your input force: MA = load ÷ effort. *Efficiency* is the percentage of input energy that becomes useful output: efficiency = (useful output ÷ total input) × 100%.

**Real-world example.** A crowbar lets a small effort lift a heavy rock (high MA); some effort is still lost to friction, so efficiency is below 100%.

**Analogy.** Mechanical advantage is like a lever letting a child lift an adult on a see-saw by sitting further out.

**Why it matters.** These measures let engineers compare and improve tools and machines.

**Worked example.** A machine lifts a 300 N load with an effort of 100 N.
MA = load ÷ effort = 300 ÷ 100 = **3** (the machine triples the force).

**Misconception.** *"A machine with a high mechanical advantage is always efficient."* Wrong — MA is about force multiplication, efficiency about energy loss; a rusty pulley can have high MA but low efficiency. Corrective: MA and efficiency are separate ideas.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *Define* mechanical advantage. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the MA of a lever lifting a 400 N load with 80 N effort. (apply)
3. *Explain* why the efficiency of a real machine is always less than 100%. (analyse)','{"100":5,"300":2,"400":1,"mechanical":5,"advantage":5,"efficiency":8,"simple":1,"machines":2,"definition":1,"how":1,"many":1,"times":1,"machine":5,"multiplies":1,"your":1,"input":3,"force":3,"load":4,"effort":6,"the":5,"percentage":1,"energy":2,"that":1,"becomes":1,"useful":2,"output":2,"total":1,"real":2,"world":1,"example":2,"crowbar":1,"lets":1,"small":1,"lift":2,"heavy":1,"rock":1,"high":3,"some":1,"still":1,"lost":1,"friction":1,"below":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"lever":2,"letting":1,"child":1,"adult":1,"see":1,"saw":1,"sitting":1,"further":1,"out":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"these":1,"measures":1,"let":1,"engineers":1,"compare":1,"and":3,"improve":1,"tools":1,"worked":1,"lifts":1,"with":3,"triples":1,"misconception":1,"always":2,"efficient":1,"wrong":1,"about":2,"multiplication":1,"loss":1,"rusty":1,"pulley":1,"can":1,"have":1,"but":1,"low":1,"corrective":1,"are":1,"separate":1,"ideas":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"define":1,"recall":1,"calculate":1,"lifting":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"less":1,"than":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_d33a5766098a93b385','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Types of Energy & Energy Transformation','**Definition.** Energy is the capacity to do work; it exists in many forms and can transform between them.

| Energy type | Description | Example transformation |
|-------------|-------------|------------------------|
| Kinetic | Energy of a moving object | Chemical → kinetic (a running person) |
| Potential (gravitational) | Stored energy due to height | Gravitational PE → kinetic (falling ball) |
| Elastic potential | Stored in stretched/compressed objects | Elastic PE → kinetic (released catapult) |
| Chemical | Stored in bonds of fuel/food/batteries | Chemical → heat + light (burning fuel) |
| Atomic (nuclear) | Stored in atomic nuclei | Nuclear → heat (reactor) |
| Heat (thermal) | Energy from particle motion/temperature | Electrical → heat (heater) |
| Mechanical | Sum of kinetic + potential energy | Mechanical → electrical (dynamo) |

**Real-world example.** A torch: chemical energy in the battery → electrical → light + heat.

**Analogy.** Energy forms are like different currencies; transformation is exchanging one for another without changing the total value.

**Why it matters.** Nearly every device works by transforming energy from one useful form to another.

**Misconception.** *"Energy gets used up and disappears."* Wrong — it transforms, often into less useful heat, but the total is conserved. Corrective: energy is transferred/transformed, never destroyed.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *List* four types of energy. (recall)
2. *Describe* the energy transformations in a swinging pendulum. (apply)
3. *Explain* why the light energy from a bulb is less than the electrical energy supplied. (analyse)','{"types":2,"energy":17,"transformation":3,"definition":1,"the":7,"capacity":1,"work":1,"exists":1,"many":1,"forms":2,"and":2,"can":1,"transform":1,"between":1,"them":1,"type":1,"description":1,"example":2,"kinetic":5,"moving":1,"object":1,"chemical":4,"running":1,"person":1,"potential":3,"gravitational":2,"stored":4,"due":1,"height":1,"falling":1,"ball":1,"elastic":2,"stretched":1,"compressed":1,"objects":1,"released":1,"catapult":1,"bonds":1,"fuel":2,"food":1,"batteries":1,"heat":6,"light":3,"burning":1,"atomic":2,"nuclear":2,"nuclei":1,"reactor":1,"thermal":1,"from":3,"particle":1,"motion":1,"temperature":1,"electrical":4,"heater":1,"mechanical":2,"sum":1,"dynamo":1,"real":1,"world":1,"torch":1,"battery":1,"analogy":1,"are":1,"like":1,"different":1,"currencies":1,"exchanging":1,"one":2,"for":1,"another":2,"without":1,"changing":1,"total":2,"value":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"nearly":1,"every":1,"device":1,"works":1,"transforming":1,"useful":2,"form":1,"misconception":1,"gets":1,"used":1,"disappears":1,"wrong":1,"transforms":1,"often":1,"into":1,"less":2,"but":1,"conserved":1,"corrective":1,"transferred":1,"transformed":1,"never":1,"destroyed":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"list":1,"four":1,"recall":1,"describe":1,"transformations":1,"swinging":1,"pendulum":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"bulb":1,"than":1,"supplied":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_7d7ee7b5cf543fbd19','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Law of Conservation of Energy (conceptual)','**Definition.** The total energy in a closed system is constant; energy only changes form. (Conceptual here — no calculations.)

**Real-world example.** A roller coaster: at the top, mostly gravitational PE; at the bottom, mostly kinetic — the total (minus friction losses) stays the same.

**Analogy.** Pouring water between cups — you can move it around, but no water appears or vanishes.

**Why it matters.** It underpins all energy analysis and rules out "free energy" devices.

**Misconception.** *"A roller coaster loses energy and that energy is gone."* Wrong — it converts to heat and sound in the rails and air. Corrective: "lost" energy is transformed, not destroyed.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* the law of conservation of energy. (recall)
2. *Describe* how energy is conserved on a roller coaster. (apply)
3. *Explain* why a pendulum eventually stops even though energy is conserved. (analyse)','{"law":2,"conservation":2,"energy":11,"conceptual":2,"definition":1,"the":7,"total":2,"closed":1,"system":1,"constant":1,"only":1,"changes":1,"form":1,"here":1,"calculations":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"roller":3,"coaster":3,"top":1,"mostly":2,"gravitational":1,"bottom":1,"kinetic":1,"minus":1,"friction":1,"losses":1,"stays":1,"same":1,"analogy":1,"pouring":1,"water":2,"between":1,"cups":1,"you":1,"can":1,"move":1,"around":1,"but":1,"appears":1,"vanishes":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"underpins":1,"all":1,"analysis":1,"and":4,"rules":1,"out":1,"free":1,"devices":1,"misconception":1,"loses":1,"that":1,"gone":1,"wrong":1,"converts":1,"heat":1,"sound":1,"rails":1,"air":1,"corrective":1,"lost":1,"transformed":1,"not":1,"destroyed":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"recall":1,"describe":1,"how":1,"conserved":2,"apply":1,"explain":1,"pendulum":1,"eventually":1,"stops":1,"even":1,"though":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_5aaf5a3035cf8023b7','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Kinetic Energy','**Definition.** Kinetic energy is the energy of a moving object: **Ek = ½ m v²**, unit joules (J).

**Real-world example.** A fast car has far more kinetic energy than a slow one — and doubling speed quadruples it, which is why high speeds are dangerous.

**Analogy.** Kinetic energy is the "punch" a moving object can deliver — heavier and faster means a bigger punch.

**Why it matters.** Explains braking distances, collisions and the danger of speed.

**Worked example.** A 2 kg ball moves at 3 m/s.
Ek = ½ m v² = ½ × 2 × 3² = ½ × 2 × 9 = **9 J**.

**Misconception.** *"Doubling the speed doubles the kinetic energy."* Wrong — because of the v² term, doubling speed *quadruples* Ek. Corrective: Ek depends on speed squared.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* the formula for kinetic energy. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the kinetic energy of a 4 kg object moving at 5 m/s. (apply)
3. *Explain* why a small increase in a car''s speed greatly increases its stopping energy. (analyse)','{"kinetic":7,"energy":9,"definition":1,"the":8,"moving":3,"object":3,"unit":1,"joules":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":2,"fast":1,"car":2,"has":1,"far":1,"more":1,"than":1,"slow":1,"one":1,"and":3,"doubling":3,"speed":6,"quadruples":2,"which":1,"why":3,"high":1,"speeds":1,"are":1,"dangerous":1,"analogy":1,"punch":2,"can":1,"deliver":1,"heavier":1,"faster":1,"means":1,"bigger":1,"matters":1,"explains":1,"braking":1,"distances":1,"collisions":1,"danger":1,"worked":1,"ball":1,"moves":1,"misconception":1,"doubles":1,"wrong":1,"because":1,"term":2,"corrective":1,"depends":1,"squared":1,"command":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"formula":1,"for":1,"recall":1,"calculate":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"small":1,"increase":1,"greatly":1,"increases":1,"its":1,"stopping":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_82bf27d387fe174196','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Gravitational Potential Energy','**Definition.** Gravitational PE is energy stored due to an object''s height in a gravitational field: **ΔEp = m g Δh**, unit joules (J), with g ≈ 10 N/kg.

**Real-world example.** Water stored high in a reservoir has gravitational PE that becomes kinetic energy as it falls to drive turbines.

**Analogy.** Lifting a book to a shelf is like "charging it up" with stored energy ready to be released if it falls.

**Why it matters.** Explains hydroelectric power, roller coasters and why falls from height are dangerous.

**Worked example.** A 3 kg object is lifted 2 m (g = 10 N/kg).
ΔEp = m g Δh = 3 × 10 × 2 = **60 J**.

**Misconception.** *"Heavier objects always have more potential energy."* Wrong — PE also depends on height; a light object placed very high can have more PE than a heavy one on the floor. Corrective: PE depends on both mass and height.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* the formula for gravitational potential energy. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the PE gained by a 2 kg book lifted 1.5 m. (apply)
3. *Explain* how a hydroelectric dam converts gravitational PE into electricity. (analyse)','{"gravitational":6,"potential":3,"energy":6,"definition":1,"stored":3,"due":1,"object":3,"height":4,"field":1,"unit":1,"joules":1,"with":2,"real":1,"world":1,"example":2,"water":1,"high":2,"reservoir":1,"has":1,"that":1,"becomes":1,"kinetic":1,"falls":3,"drive":1,"turbines":1,"analogy":1,"lifting":1,"book":2,"shelf":1,"like":1,"charging":1,"ready":1,"released":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"explains":1,"hydroelectric":2,"power":1,"roller":1,"coasters":1,"and":2,"from":1,"are":1,"dangerous":1,"worked":1,"lifted":2,"misconception":1,"heavier":1,"objects":1,"always":1,"have":2,"more":2,"wrong":1,"also":1,"depends":2,"light":1,"placed":1,"very":1,"can":1,"than":1,"heavy":1,"one":1,"the":3,"floor":1,"corrective":1,"both":1,"mass":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"formula":1,"for":1,"recall":1,"calculate":1,"gained":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"how":1,"dam":1,"converts":1,"into":1,"electricity":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_d43e0fc3a5daac5eaa','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Elastic Potential Energy','**Definition.** Elastic potential energy is energy stored in a stretched or compressed object such as a spring or rubber band. (Mentioned as a type at this level.)

**Real-world example.** A drawn bow stores elastic PE that becomes the arrow''s kinetic energy on release.

**Analogy.** A loaded spring is like a coiled snake, holding energy ready to spring out.

**Why it matters.** Explains catapults, trampolines, and clockwork mechanisms.

**Misconception.** *"Only metal springs store elastic energy."* Wrong — any elastic material (rubber, bungee cords) stores it when deformed. Corrective: elastic PE is stored in any stretched or compressed elastic object.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *Define* elastic potential energy. (recall)
2. *Identify* the energy stored in a stretched catapult. (apply)
3. *Explain* the energy transformation when a compressed spring is released. (analyse)','{"elastic":8,"potential":3,"energy":9,"definition":1,"stored":3,"stretched":3,"compressed":3,"object":2,"such":1,"spring":4,"rubber":2,"band":1,"mentioned":1,"type":1,"this":1,"level":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"drawn":1,"bow":1,"stores":2,"that":1,"becomes":1,"the":3,"arrow":1,"kinetic":1,"release":1,"analogy":1,"loaded":1,"like":1,"coiled":1,"snake":1,"holding":1,"ready":1,"out":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"explains":1,"catapults":1,"trampolines":1,"and":1,"clockwork":1,"mechanisms":1,"misconception":1,"only":1,"metal":1,"springs":1,"store":1,"wrong":1,"any":2,"material":1,"bungee":1,"cords":1,"when":2,"deformed":1,"corrective":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"define":1,"recall":1,"identify":1,"catapult":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"transformation":1,"released":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_e3d338b30581759bec','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Work Done','**Definition.** Work is done when a force moves an object in the direction of the force: **W = force × displacement (in the same direction)**, unit joules (J).

**Real-world example.** Pushing a trolley 5 m across a shop does work; holding a heavy bag still does *no* physics work (no movement).

**Analogy.** Work is the "effort that actually got the job moved along" — straining without movement doesn''t count.

**Why it matters.** Work is the link between force and energy transfer.

**Worked example.** A force of 20 N pushes a box 4 m in the direction of the force.
W = F × displacement = 20 × 4 = **80 J**.

**Misconception.** *"You do work just by pushing hard on a wall."* Wrong — if the wall doesn''t move, displacement is zero, so work done is zero, however tiring. Corrective: no movement in the force''s direction = no work done.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* the formula for work done. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the work done lifting a box with a 50 N force through 3 m. (apply)
3. *Explain* why holding a heavy weight still does no physics work. (analyse)','{"work":12,"done":6,"definition":1,"when":1,"force":8,"moves":1,"object":1,"the":12,"direction":4,"displacement":3,"same":1,"unit":1,"joules":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":2,"pushing":2,"trolley":1,"across":1,"shop":1,"does":3,"holding":2,"heavy":2,"bag":1,"still":2,"physics":2,"movement":3,"analogy":1,"effort":1,"that":1,"actually":1,"got":1,"job":1,"moved":1,"along":1,"straining":1,"without":1,"doesn":2,"count":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"link":1,"between":1,"and":1,"energy":1,"transfer":1,"worked":1,"pushes":1,"box":2,"misconception":1,"you":1,"just":1,"hard":1,"wall":2,"wrong":1,"move":1,"zero":2,"however":1,"tiring":1,"corrective":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"formula":1,"for":1,"recall":1,"calculate":1,"lifting":1,"with":1,"through":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"weight":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_388f97de8ccd515989','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Power','**Definition.** Power is the rate of doing work (or transferring energy): **power = work done ÷ time**, unit watt (W), where 1 W = 1 J/s.

**Real-world example.** Two cranes lift the same load, but the more powerful one does it faster.

**Analogy.** Power is like how fast you can eat a pizza — same pizza (work), but a faster eater has more "power."

**Why it matters.** Power rates appliances and machines, telling us how quickly they deliver energy.

**Worked example.** A motor does 600 J of work in 4 s.
Power = work ÷ time = 600 ÷ 4 = **150 W**.

**Misconception.** *"A more powerful machine always does more total work."* Wrong — power is about *speed* of doing work; two machines can do equal work, the more powerful one just does it faster. Corrective: power = work per unit time, not total work.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* the unit of power. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the power of a device doing 900 J in 3 s. (apply)
3. *Explain* the difference between two engines with the same work output but different power. (analyse)','{"150":1,"600":2,"900":1,"power":12,"definition":1,"the":8,"rate":1,"doing":3,"work":11,"transferring":1,"energy":2,"done":1,"time":3,"unit":3,"watt":1,"where":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":2,"two":3,"cranes":1,"lift":1,"same":3,"load":1,"but":3,"more":5,"powerful":3,"one":2,"does":4,"faster":3,"analogy":1,"like":1,"how":2,"fast":1,"you":1,"can":2,"eat":1,"pizza":2,"eater":1,"has":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"rates":1,"appliances":1,"and":1,"machines":2,"telling":1,"quickly":1,"they":1,"deliver":1,"worked":1,"motor":1,"misconception":1,"machine":1,"always":1,"total":2,"wrong":1,"about":1,"speed":1,"equal":1,"just":1,"corrective":1,"per":1,"not":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"recall":1,"calculate":1,"device":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"difference":1,"between":1,"engines":1,"with":1,"output":1,"different":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_f5f1562c8591e6eb7d','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Efficiency & Sankey Diagrams','**Definition.** Efficiency is the fraction of input energy transformed into useful output, as a percentage: **efficiency = (useful energy output ÷ total energy input) × 100%**. A *Sankey diagram* shows energy flow as arrows whose widths are proportional to the energy — the useful output continues forward and wasted energy branches off.

**Real-world example.** An LED bulb turning most electrical energy into light is more efficient than an old filament bulb that wastes most as heat.

**Analogy.** A Sankey diagram is like a river splitting into a main channel (useful energy) and side streams (wasted energy) — the widths add up to the source.

**Why it matters.** Efficiency guides energy-saving design and reduces waste.

**Described diagram.** For a bulb: a wide arrow of "100 J electrical" enters; a narrow "20 J light" arrow continues (useful) and an "80 J heat" arrow branches downward (wasted). Widths are drawn to scale.

**Worked example.** A lamp takes in 100 J and gives out 20 J of light.
Efficiency = (20 ÷ 100) × 100 = **20%**.

**Misconception.** *"Wasted energy in a Sankey diagram just disappears."* Wrong — it is still counted (often as heat) so total in = total out; the arrows must balance. Corrective: input width = useful width + wasted width (energy conserved).

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* the formula for efficiency. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the efficiency of a motor using 400 J to produce 300 J of useful output. (apply)
3. *Interpret* a Sankey diagram to identify where energy is wasted and suggest an improvement. (evaluate)','{"100":5,"300":1,"400":1,"efficiency":7,"sankey":5,"diagrams":1,"definition":1,"the":8,"fraction":1,"input":3,"energy":13,"transformed":1,"into":3,"useful":7,"output":4,"percentage":1,"total":3,"diagram":5,"shows":1,"flow":1,"arrows":2,"whose":1,"widths":3,"are":2,"proportional":1,"continues":2,"forward":1,"and":6,"wasted":6,"branches":2,"off":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":2,"led":1,"bulb":3,"turning":1,"most":2,"electrical":2,"light":3,"more":1,"efficient":1,"than":1,"old":1,"filament":1,"that":1,"wastes":1,"heat":3,"analogy":1,"like":1,"river":1,"splitting":1,"main":1,"channel":1,"side":1,"streams":1,"add":1,"source":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"guides":1,"saving":1,"design":1,"reduces":1,"waste":1,"described":1,"for":2,"wide":1,"arrow":3,"enters":1,"narrow":1,"downward":1,"drawn":1,"scale":1,"worked":1,"lamp":1,"takes":1,"gives":1,"out":2,"misconception":1,"just":1,"disappears":1,"wrong":1,"still":1,"counted":1,"often":1,"must":1,"balance":1,"corrective":1,"width":3,"conserved":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"formula":1,"recall":1,"calculate":1,"motor":1,"using":1,"produce":1,"apply":1,"interpret":1,"identify":1,"where":1,"suggest":1,"improvement":1,"evaluate":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_72651b1cc03d1bfef2','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Energy Resources: Renewable & Non-Renewable','**Definition.** *Renewable* resources are naturally replenished on a human timescale (solar, wind, hydro, tidal); *non-renewable* resources (coal, oil, gas, nuclear fuel) exist in finite amounts and run out. The **Sun is the ultimate source** of most of Earth''s energy (driving wind, waves, hydro cycle, and stored in fossil fuels).

| Resource | Type | Advantage | Disadvantage |
|----------|------|-----------|--------------|
| Solar | Renewable | Clean, unlimited sunlight | Depends on weather/daylight |
| Wind | Renewable | No fuel cost, low emissions | Intermittent, needs wind |
| Hydro | Renewable | Reliable, large scale | Dams disrupt ecosystems |
| Tidal | Renewable | Predictable | High build cost, few sites |
| Fossil fuels | Non-renewable | High energy density, reliable | Pollution, CO₂, finite |

**Real-world example.** Solar farms and wind turbines increasingly replace coal power stations to cut carbon emissions.

**Analogy.** Renewable energy is like a well that refills; non-renewable is a tank that empties for good.

**Why it matters.** The choice of energy resources affects climate, economy and sustainability — central to MYP Criterion D.

**Implications & latest discoveries.** Advances include higher-efficiency perovskite solar cells, floating offshore wind farms, large grid-scale batteries for storing renewable energy, green hydrogen produced from renewable electricity, and progress toward nuclear fusion for clean, high-output power. These aim to reduce fossil-fuel dependence and greenhouse emissions.

**Misconception.** *"Renewable energy produces no pollution at all."* Wrong — manufacturing panels/turbines and building dams have environmental costs, even if running them is clean. Corrective: renewables are far cleaner in operation but not entirely impact-free.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *List* three renewable energy resources. (recall)
2. *Classify* natural gas and tidal power as renewable or non-renewable. (apply)
3. *Evaluate* whether a coastal town should invest in tidal power, considering advantages, disadvantages and implications. (evaluate)','{"energy":8,"resources":5,"renewable":17,"non":5,"definition":1,"are":2,"naturally":1,"replenished":1,"human":1,"timescale":1,"solar":4,"wind":6,"hydro":3,"tidal":4,"coal":2,"oil":1,"gas":2,"nuclear":2,"fuel":3,"exist":1,"finite":2,"amounts":1,"and":9,"run":1,"out":1,"the":3,"sun":1,"ultimate":1,"source":1,"most":1,"earth":1,"driving":1,"waves":1,"cycle":1,"stored":1,"fossil":3,"fuels":2,"resource":1,"type":1,"advantage":1,"disadvantage":1,"clean":3,"unlimited":1,"sunlight":1,"depends":1,"weather":1,"daylight":1,"cost":2,"low":1,"emissions":3,"intermittent":1,"needs":1,"reliable":2,"large":2,"scale":2,"dams":2,"disrupt":1,"ecosystems":1,"predictable":1,"high":3,"build":1,"few":1,"sites":1,"density":1,"pollution":2,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"farms":2,"turbines":2,"increasingly":1,"replace":1,"power":4,"stations":1,"cut":1,"carbon":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"well":1,"that":2,"refills":1,"tank":1,"empties":1,"for":3,"good":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"choice":1,"affects":1,"climate":1,"economy":1,"sustainability":1,"central":1,"myp":1,"criterion":1,"implications":2,"latest":1,"discoveries":1,"advances":1,"include":1,"higher":1,"efficiency":1,"perovskite":1,"cells":1,"floating":1,"offshore":1,"grid":1,"batteries":1,"storing":1,"green":1,"hydrogen":1,"produced":1,"from":1,"electricity":1,"progress":1,"toward":1,"fusion":1,"output":1,"these":1,"aim":1,"reduce":1,"dependence":1,"greenhouse":1,"misconception":1,"produces":1,"all":1,"wrong":1,"manufacturing":1,"panels":1,"building":1,"have":1,"environmental":1,"costs":1,"even":1,"running":1,"them":1,"corrective":1,"renewables":1,"far":1,"cleaner":1,"operation":1,"but":1,"not":1,"entirely":1,"impact":1,"free":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"list":1,"three":1,"recall":1,"classify":1,"natural":1,"apply":1,"evaluate":2,"whether":1,"coastal":1,"town":1,"should":1,"invest":1,"considering":1,"advantages":1,"disadvantages":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_ed2bd4b97093c93969','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Properties of Magnets','**Definition.** A magnet has two poles — north (N) and south (S). Poles always occur in pairs; like poles repel, unlike poles attract. The force is strongest at the poles.

**Real-world example.** A compass needle (a small magnet) turns so its north pole points toward Earth''s magnetic north.

**Analogy.** Like poles are like two people who dislike each other backing away; unlike poles are like friends drawn together.

**Why it matters.** These rules underlie compasses, motors, generators and data storage.

**Misconception.** *"You can get a single north pole by cutting a magnet in half."* Wrong — each piece becomes a new complete magnet with both N and S poles. Corrective: poles always exist in pairs (no magnetic monopole).

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* the rule for like and unlike magnetic poles. (recall)
2. *Predict* what happens when the north poles of two magnets are brought together. (apply)
3. *Explain* why breaking a bar magnet does not isolate a single pole. (analyse)','{"properties":1,"magnets":2,"definition":1,"magnet":5,"has":1,"two":3,"poles":11,"north":5,"and":4,"south":1,"always":2,"occur":1,"pairs":2,"like":5,"repel":1,"unlike":3,"attract":1,"the":4,"force":1,"strongest":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"compass":1,"needle":1,"small":1,"turns":1,"its":1,"pole":3,"points":1,"toward":1,"earth":1,"magnetic":3,"analogy":1,"are":3,"people":1,"who":1,"dislike":1,"each":2,"other":1,"backing":1,"away":1,"friends":1,"drawn":1,"together":2,"why":2,"matters":1,"these":1,"rules":1,"underlie":1,"compasses":1,"motors":1,"generators":1,"data":1,"storage":1,"misconception":1,"you":1,"can":1,"get":1,"single":2,"cutting":1,"half":1,"wrong":1,"piece":1,"becomes":1,"new":1,"complete":1,"with":1,"both":1,"corrective":1,"exist":1,"monopole":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"rule":1,"for":1,"recall":1,"predict":1,"what":1,"happens":1,"when":1,"brought":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"breaking":1,"bar":1,"does":1,"not":1,"isolate":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_d35031a61883c86610','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Magnetic vs Non-Magnetic Materials','**Definition.** *Magnetic materials* (iron, nickel, cobalt and steel) are attracted to magnets; *non-magnetic materials* (plastic, wood, copper, aluminium, glass) are not.

**Real-world example.** A magnet picks up steel paper clips but not plastic or aluminium ones.

**Analogy.** Magnetic materials "answer the call" of a magnet; non-magnetic ones ignore it.

**Why it matters.** Sorting scrap metal, magnetic separation and design of devices depend on knowing which materials respond.

**Misconception.** *"All metals are magnetic."* Wrong — copper, gold and aluminium are metals but not magnetic. Corrective: only certain metals (iron, nickel, cobalt and their alloys) are magnetic.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *List* two magnetic and two non-magnetic materials. (recall)
2. *Identify* whether an aluminium can is attracted to a magnet. (apply)
3. *Explain* how a magnet could be used to separate iron filings from sand. (analyse)','{"magnetic":12,"non":4,"materials":6,"definition":1,"iron":3,"nickel":2,"cobalt":2,"and":5,"steel":2,"are":5,"attracted":2,"magnets":1,"plastic":2,"wood":1,"copper":2,"aluminium":4,"glass":1,"not":3,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"magnet":4,"picks":1,"paper":1,"clips":1,"but":2,"ones":2,"analogy":1,"answer":1,"the":1,"call":1,"ignore":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"sorting":1,"scrap":1,"metal":1,"separation":1,"design":1,"devices":1,"depend":1,"knowing":1,"which":1,"respond":1,"misconception":1,"all":1,"metals":3,"wrong":1,"gold":1,"corrective":1,"only":1,"certain":1,"their":1,"alloys":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"list":1,"two":2,"recall":1,"identify":1,"whether":1,"can":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"how":1,"could":1,"used":1,"separate":1,"filings":1,"from":1,"sand":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_367542945f7c91e6c3','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Magnetic Field Lines','**Definition.** A magnetic field is the region around a magnet where its force acts. *Field lines* are drawn from N to S outside the magnet; they never cross, and where they are closer together the field is stronger.

**Real-world example.** Iron filings sprinkled around a bar magnet arrange themselves along the field lines, revealing the pattern.

**Analogy.** Field lines are like invisible "wind currents" flowing out of the north pole and into the south pole.

**Why it matters.** Field lines let us visualise an invisible force and predict how magnets and compasses behave.

**Described diagram (bar magnet field lines).** Curved lines leave the N pole, loop around the outside, and enter the S pole; lines are densest and most tightly packed near the poles (strongest field) and more spread out at the sides (weaker field). Arrows point from N to S outside the magnet.

**Using a compass.** Place a plotting compass near the magnet; the needle aligns with the field. Mark the direction at many points and join them to trace the field lines.

**Misconception.** *"Magnetic field lines can cross each other."* Wrong — crossing would mean two field directions at one point, which is impossible. Corrective: field lines never intersect.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* the direction field lines point outside a magnet. (recall)
2. *Describe* how iron filings reveal a magnet''s field. (apply)
3. *Explain* what the spacing of field lines tells you about field strength. (analyse)','{"magnetic":3,"field":19,"lines":13,"definition":1,"the":20,"region":1,"around":3,"magnet":8,"where":2,"its":1,"force":2,"acts":1,"are":4,"drawn":1,"from":2,"outside":4,"they":2,"never":2,"cross":2,"and":8,"closer":1,"together":1,"stronger":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"iron":2,"filings":2,"sprinkled":1,"bar":2,"arrange":1,"themselves":1,"along":1,"revealing":1,"pattern":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"invisible":2,"wind":1,"currents":1,"flowing":1,"out":2,"north":1,"pole":4,"into":1,"south":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"let":1,"visualise":1,"predict":1,"how":2,"magnets":1,"compasses":1,"behave":1,"described":1,"diagram":1,"curved":1,"leave":1,"loop":1,"enter":1,"densest":1,"most":1,"tightly":1,"packed":1,"near":2,"poles":1,"strongest":1,"more":1,"spread":1,"sides":1,"weaker":1,"arrows":1,"point":3,"using":1,"compass":2,"place":1,"plotting":1,"needle":1,"aligns":1,"with":1,"mark":1,"direction":2,"many":1,"points":1,"join":1,"them":1,"trace":1,"misconception":1,"can":1,"each":1,"other":1,"wrong":1,"crossing":1,"would":1,"mean":1,"two":1,"directions":1,"one":1,"which":1,"impossible":1,"corrective":1,"intersect":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"recall":1,"describe":1,"reveal":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"what":1,"spacing":1,"tells":1,"you":1,"about":1,"strength":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb);